The result above is returned after performing an aggressive port scan against the three TCP ports using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.129.50.49 -p 21,22,80. There is an interesting web application on port 80. I will start my enumeration at this port as FTP does not allow anonymous login, and I do not have any credentials for SSH.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this web application. There is an interesting user called Nathan that is already logged into the system. Maybe I can access sensitive information as this user? Time to dig around for crucial information.


Pressing the hamburger icon from the previous image displays the webpage above. There are more options available such as the IP Config, Network Status, and Security Snapshot.


I found the Security Snapshot page the most interesting. This webpage is shown above. The URL /data/1 is interesting too. There are eight packets. Pressing the Download button downloads a PCAP file. Is this web application vulnerable to IDOR? What happens if I use different integers as the data input; for example, what about 0?


And bingo! Browsing to http://10.129.50.49/data/0 displays the webpage above. The number of packets changed from eight to seventy-two! Maybe this Wireshark capture file contains sensitive information?


Reading through the Wireshark capture file, I found the FTP credentials above. Packet 40 contains the password Buck3tH4TF0RM3! of user nathan, as shown above. This can be filtered further by using the filter command tcp.stream eq 3 as shown above. Armed with new FTP credentials, time to use it against the FTP and SSH now.

Exploitation


Using the credentials inside the Wireshark capture file, I am able to login to the SSH application as the user nathan as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as the user nathan via SSH. The local.txt flag is accessible. The command I used is ssh nathan@10.129.50.49, and then the password Buck3tH4TF0RM3!.

Privilege Escalation


After some manual enumeration, I found the interesting result above. Running the command /usr/sbin/getcap / -r 2>/dev/null returns the interesting /usr/bin/python3.8 = cap_setuid,cap_net_bind_service+eip entry, as shown above. The Python binary has misconfigured capabilities set, thus allowing privilege escalation.


And bingo! Using the command /usr/bin/python3.8 -c 'import os; os.setuid(0); os.system("/bin/sh")', I was able to open a root shell using the misconfigured Python binary with capabilities set. Now I have root access on the target machine :)
